.TH BYN 1 "2026-06-03" "byn 0.0.1" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
byn \- secure secrets vault with shim-based credential injection
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B byn
[\fIcommand\fR] [\fIargs...\fR]
.PP
.B byn help
[\fIcommand\fR]
.PP
.B byn
\fIcommand\fR
.B \-\-help
.PP
.B byn
\fIcommand\fR
.B help
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B byn
stores secrets locally in an encrypted vault and serves them through a
background daemon. The CLI is a thin client; the daemon owns all
business logic, encryption keys, and file state.
.PP
The vault key is a 32\-byte random key, sealed at rest by Argon2id of
the master password. Each secret value is encrypted with
XChaCha20\-Poly1305 keyed by the vault key, with the ciphertext bound
to the entry's identity via AEAD additional data.
.PP
Default daemon data directory is
.IR ~/.byn/ .
Override with
.B BYN_DIR
in the environment.
.SH COMMANDS
.SS Setup and lifecycle
.TP
.B init
Create a fresh vault. Prompts for the master password twice. Targets
the vault named by \fB\-\-vault\fR (or \fIBYN_VAULT\fR), defaulting
to \fIdefault\fR. Vaults live under
\fI$BYN_DIR/vaults/<name>/\fR.
See
.BR byn-init (1).
.TP
.B unlock
Unlock the vault for the current daemon session. Prompts for the
master password.
See
.BR byn-unlock (1).
.TP
.B lock \fR[\fB\-\-all\fR]
Lock the vault by zeroing the in\-memory vault key.
.B \-\-all
locks every unlocked vault.
See
.BR byn-lock (1).
.TP
.B passwd \fR[\fB\-\-password\-stdin\fR]
Change the vault's master password by re\-wrapping the vault key. The
current password is required; data and lock state are preserved. With
.B \-\-password\-stdin
the current and new passwords are read as two lines from standard input.
A forgotten password is unrecoverable by design.
.TP
.B status
Print daemon and vault state. Alias for \fBdaemon status\fR.
Accepts \fB\-\-json\fR for the raw StatusResp payload.
See
.BR byn-status (1).
.SS Structure (vault / project / env)
.TP
.B vault list \fR[\fB\-\-json\fR]
List every vault present on disk under
.IR $BYN_DIR/vaults/ .
.TP
.B vault delete \fINAME\fR \fR[\fB\-\-password\-stdin\fR]
Securely remove a vault from disk (overwrites the wrapped key, then
removes the directory; the audit log is kept). Refuses the \fIdefault\fR
vault. See \fBDELETING WHILE LOCKED\fR below.
.TP
.B vault rename \fIOLD NEW\fR \fR[\fB\-\-password\-stdin\fR]
Rename a vault (and its audit trail) on disk. Refuses the \fIdefault\fR
vault and an existing destination. Crypto\-safe (the value encryption binds
to the vault id, not its name). The vault is left LOCKED afterwards. A
locked vault is renamed with the password, like a delete.
.TP
.B vault passwd
Alias for the top\-level \fBpasswd\fR command.
.TP
.B vault init \fR| \fBvault unlock \fR| \fBvault lock\fR
Aliases for the top\-level lifecycle commands; provided so muscle
memory works either way.
.TP
.B project list \fR[\fB\-\-json\fR]
List projects in the active vault.
.TP
.B project create \fINAME\fR
Create a project and its implicit \fIdefault\fR env.
.TP
.B project delete \fINAME\fR \fR[\fB\-\-password\-stdin\fR]
Cascade\-delete the project, its envs, entries, and entry_versions.
Refuses \fIdefault\fR. See \fBDELETING WHILE LOCKED\fR below.
.TP
.B project rename \fIOLD\fR \fINEW\fR
Rename a project.
.TP
.B env list \fR[\fB\-\-json\fR]
List envs in the active project. The default env is pinned first.
.TP
.B env create \fINAME\fR
Create a non\-default env. Other envs inherit from \fIdefault\fR for
missing keys.
.TP
.B env delete \fINAME\fR \fR[\fB\-\-password\-stdin\fR]
Remove a non\-default env (cascades to its entries). Refuses
\fIdefault\fR. See \fBDELETING WHILE LOCKED\fR below.
.TP
.B env clear \fR[\fIENV\fR] \fB\-\-yes\fR \fR[\fB\-\-password\-stdin\fR]
Delete every env\-var in \fIENV\fR (defaults to the active env) while
keeping the env itself; inherited values from \fIdefault\fR are untouched.
Destructive, so \fB\-\-yes\fR is required \(em without it, prints a preview
and exits non\-zero. Password\-gated like a delete.
.TP
.B env rename \fIOLD\fR \fINEW\fR
Rename an env.
.SS Secret CRUD
.TP
.B put \fINAME\fR
Store a secret. The value is read from stdin; piping or redirection
is required so the value never appears in argv or shell history.
See
.BR byn-put (1).
.TP
.B get \fINAME\fR
Print a secret's decrypted value to stdout. Alias:
.BR cat .
See
.BR byn-get (1).
.TP
.B list \fR[\fINAME\fR|\fIGLOB\fR]
List secret names. Works while the vault is locked (the index is
plaintext metadata; only values require unlock). With a
.I NAME
or
.I GLOB
argument it is grep\-like: prints only matching names, exits 0 when at
least one matches, or prints nothing and exits 1 when none do \(em an
existence check that never reads a value. Alias:
.BR ls .
See
.BR byn-list (1).
.TP
.B delete \fINAME\fR \fR[\fB\-\-password\-stdin\fR]
Remove a secret from the vault. Alias:
.BR rm .
See \fBDELETING WHILE LOCKED\fR below and
.BR byn-delete (1).
.TP
.B rename \fIOLD\fR \fINEW\fR
Move a secret to a new name. Re\-encrypts under the new name's AAD,
so unlock is required. Alias:
.BR mv .
See
.BR byn-rename (1).
.TP
.B exec \fB\-\-\fR \fICOMMAND\fR \fR[\fIARGS...\fR]
Inject env\-vars into a child process. See COMMANDS \(-> "Run with
env\-vars injected" above.
.SS Run with env-vars injected
.TP
.B exec \fB\-\-\fR \fICOMMAND\fR \fR[\fIARGS...\fR]
Loads every env\-var entry in the active vault scope and replaces the
current byn process with \fICOMMAND\fR via \fBexecve\fR(2), passing
the loaded entries plus the existing environment to the child. The
child's PID is the same as the byn CLI that invoked it. Values
never appear in the parent shell or argv. The "\fB\-\-\fR" separator
is required.
Only exec verifies the \fB.byn\fR is trusted (machine + vault\-key MAC)
before injecting; an untrusted, changed, or tampered \fB.byn\fR aborts
\(em other commands apply a \fB.byn\fR scope without a trust check.
A discovered \fB.byn\fR also controls which vars exec injects via
\fB[exec] env\fR: a name list injects only those, \fB"*"\fR injects all
(with a warning), and an empty or absent list injects nothing; with no
\fB.byn\fR (ad\-hoc) the whole scope is injected. \fB[exec] env\fR is
ENV\-VARS ONLY \(em it does not restrict which command runs. The
\fB.byn\fR is strict TOML: any key outside \fB[scope]\fR / \fB[exec] env\fR
is a hard parse error.
See
.BR byn-exec (1).
.SS Bulk I/O
.TP
.B import \fR[\fB\-\-format\fR \fIenv\fR|\fIyaml\fR|\fIjson\fR] \fR[\fB\-\-dry\-run\fR] \fR[\fB\-\-skip\-existing\fR | \fB\-\-replace\fR \fR[\fB\-\-yes\fR]] \fR[\fIPATH\fR | \fB\-\fR]
Bulk\-load key/value entries into the active scope from a
\fB.env\fR, YAML, or JSON file (or stdin). Format is inferred from
the file extension first, then sniffed (a leading "{" implies JSON);
\fB\-\-format\fR forces it. Nested objects are rejected with a clear
error pointing at the offending key. \fB\-\-dry\-run\fR prints what
would be written (key + byte length, never the value) \- and when
combined with \fB\-\-replace\fR, also the entries that would be
deleted.
.IP
Three modes (mutually exclusive):
\fBmerge\fR (default) adds new keys, overwrites matching ones, and
leaves other keys in the scope untouched;
\fB\-\-skip\-existing\fR refuses to overwrite (add\-only);
\fB\-\-replace\fR wipes every existing key in the scope first, then
imports. \fB\-\-replace\fR prompts in interactive terminals;
\fB\-\-yes\fR skips the prompt and is required in non\-TTY / agent
mode.
.IP
Dotenv parser supports: \fBexport\fR PREFIX, double\-quoted values
with \\n / \\t / \\" / \\\\ escapes, single\-quoted literals,
inline \fB# comment\fR stripping, and blank/comment lines. YAML/JSON
scalars (string, bool, number, null) are coerced to strings; anything
deeper than a flat map is rejected.
.TP
.B export \fR[\fB\-\-format\fR \fIenv\fR|\fIyaml\fR|\fIjson\fR] \fR[\fB\-\-output\fR \fIPATH\fR]
Dump every entry in the active scope as a flat key/value document.
Default format is \fBenv\fR. \fB\-\-output\fR writes to disk with
mode 0600; otherwise output goes to stdout. Keys are sorted
alphabetically. Dotenv values containing whitespace, "#", "=", or "
are wrapped in double quotes with standard escapes.
.IP
.B Caveat:
this materialises plaintext. Treat the destination as you would a
\fB.env\fR file \- never commit, never share.
.SS Diagnostics and audit
.TP
.B doctor \fR[\fB\-\-json\fR]
Run a battery of self\-checks against the daemon and every vault on
disk: daemon liveness, vault enumeration, schema + fingerprint
match, audit\-chain HMAC integrity. Each check returns
\fBok\fR / \fBwarn\fR / \fBfail\fR. Exits non\-zero if any
\fBfail\fR.
.TP
.B audit view \fR[\fB\-\-lines\fR \fIN\fR] \fR[\fB\-\-json\fR]
Snapshot the most recent \fIN\fR events from the active vault's audit
log (default 50; \fB\-\-lines 0\fR returns all) and exit. Allowed while
locked \- log metadata is not secret. Each row ends with the caller
for forensics: surface (\fBsocket\fR = CLI/TUI, \fBportal\fR =
browser), process name, pid/uid, and the parent process (who invoked
it) \- e.g. \fIsocket:byn(pid 9123, uid 501)\(<-node\fR. A reveal in
the browser or TUI routes through \fBget\fR and is logged as such.
.TP
.B audit tail \fR[\fB\-n\fR \fIN\fR] \fR[\fB\-f\fR] \fR[\fB\-\-json\fR]
Like \fBtail\fR(1): print the last \fIN\fR events (default 10) and
exit. With \fB\-f\fR, follow \- stream new events in realtime until
Ctrl\-C (NDJSON when combined with \fB\-\-json\fR).
.TP
.B audit verify \fR[\fB\-\-json\fR]
Re\-walk the active vault's audit log and recompute the HMAC chain
end\-to\-end. Exits 0 with "chain intact" on success; exits 3 with
"chain BROKEN at event #N" if any link fails verification.
.SS Trust (\fB.byn\fR TOFU)
.TP
.B trust \fR[\fIPATH\fR...] \fR[\fB\-\-paths\fR \fI"a,b,c"\fR] \fR[\fB\-\-recursive\fR] \fR[\fB\-\-password\-stdin\fR]
Approve one or more \fB.byn\fR files (default:
.IR ./.byn ;
a directory resolves to \fI<dir>/.byn\fR, and \fB\-\-recursive\fR walks
directories for every \fB.byn\fR). Files are grouped by their target vault,
so each vault's password is asked once.
\fBAlways prompts for the master password\fR \(em even when the vault is
unlocked \(em because approving a \fB.byn\fR is a proof\-of\-presence action.
The daemon (which owns
.IR ~/.byn/trusted_byn.json )
verifies the password against the vault the \fB.byn\fR targets, then records
the canonical path plus SHA\-256 of the contents. If the file already exists
in the store with a different hash (changed since trusted), \fBtrust\fR warns
before re\-approving. Discovery never auto\-trusts: a new or changed \fB.byn\fR
is refused until you run this command. Use \fB\-\-password\-stdin\fR to read
the password from stdin in scripts.
.TP
.B trust list \fR[\fB\-\-json\fR]
Print every trusted path with the first 12 hex chars of its hash.
.TP
.B untrust \fR[\fIPATH\fR...] \fR[\fB\-\-paths\fR \fI"a,b,c"\fR] \fR[\fB\-\-recursive\fR]
Revoke trust for one or more paths (default:
.IR ./.byn ),
using the same path forms as \fBtrust\fR (directories, \fB\-\-paths\fR,
\fB\-\-recursive\fR). Needs no password \(em revoking is fail-safe \(em and is
idempotent.
.SS Visual editor
.TP
.B edit, view, byn \fR(no args)
Open the responsive bubbletea TUI. Left rail navigates
vault/project/env; main pane shows ENV-VARS + FILES + RECENT AUDIT;
right detail pane on Large terminals (>= 120 cols).
.IP
Honors
.B \-\-vault ,
.B \-\-project ,
.B \-\-env
on launch \- bootstrap prompts for the targeted vault's password
and lands the rail cursor on the most\-specific matching node.
.IP
\fBvi\-style draft semantics\fR: typing modifies a local buffer only;
the daemon is not contacted. Use
.B :w
to commit,
.B :q
to leave edit context (refuses dirty),
.B :q!
to discard, or
.B :wq
to commit and leave.
.B ESC
preserves the draft. Dirty drafts are surfaced as a red
\fB[DRAFT: NAME]\fR chip in the status line plus a \fB[*]\fR prefix
on the affected entry row.
.IP
\fBvim commands\fR: \fBu\fR undoes,
.B Ctrl\-R
redoes (per\-keystroke history, capped at 200 per draft). \fBy\fR
yanks the selected entry's value to the system clipboard (fires a
daemon get + audit event). \fBp\fR pastes the clipboard into the
draft at cursor.
.B Ctrl\-V
pastes inline while in INSERT mode.
.IP
\fBInheritance badges\fR in non\-default envs:
.B \(da
(inherited from default),
.B \(la
(overrides default), and
.B \(de
(new in this env).
.IP
Alias:
.BR view .
See
.BR byn-edit (1)
and
.IR docs/tui-design.md
for the full design.
.SS Deleting while locked
The deletes \(em
.BR delete / rm ,
.BR "project delete" ,
.BR "env delete" ,
and
.BR "vault delete"
\(em touch only names, never values, so they never need the vault key. A
locked vault therefore accepts them when you supply the master password:
the daemon verifies it and proceeds WITHOUT unlocking the vault, so its
other values are never exposed to a watching process. Interactively, the
CLI prompts for the password when it finds the vault locked; for scripts,
pass
.B \-\-password\-stdin
to read it from standard input (the flag must precede the name). A wrong
password is rejected and rate\-limited like
.BR unlock .
By contrast, ADDING or editing a value needs the key to encrypt and so
cannot be done while locked \(em unlock first.
.SS Web portal
.TP
.B web, ui
Open the browser admin portal hosted by the daemon at
.I http://localhost:2967
(configurable via \fB[ui] port\fR in \fI~/.byn/config\fR). A web UI over
the same vault as the CLI and TUI. There is no portal login: like
\fBbyn ls\fR, the scope tree and entry names are visible, but reading or
editing VALUES requires the target vault to be unlocked \(em a per\-vault
lock/unlock toggle in the UI. Browse vault/project/env, create/delete
scopes and vaults, view/edit env\-var entries, and reveal values (each
reveal is audited). Binds loopback only; CSRF is defended by an Origin
check. Disable with \fB[ui] enabled = false\fR. See \fBbyn-web\fR(1).
.SS Daemon control
.TP
.B start \fR[\fB\-\-foreground\fR]
Start the daemon (detached by default). Alias: \fBbyn daemon start\fR.
.TP
.B stop
SIGTERM the daemon via its pidfile. Alias: \fBbyn daemon stop\fR.
.TP
.B restart \fR[\fB\-\-foreground\fR]
Stop the running daemon (if any) and start a fresh one \- one command
instead of stop + start. Picks up a new binary and config. Alias:
\fBbyn daemon restart\fR.
.TP
.B reload
Signal the running daemon (SIGHUP) to re-read
.I ~/.byn/config
and apply runtime-changeable settings \- idle_timeout and the web portal
(enable/disable/port) \- without a restart. Open vaults stay unlocked.
Alias: \fBbyn daemon reload\fR.
.TP
.B daemon status
Print daemon state and uptime.
.TP
.B daemon install
Register the daemon as a user auto-start service (launchd LaunchAgent on
macOS, a systemd \fB\-\-user\fR unit on Linux) so it starts on login.
Writes the service file, loads it best-effort, and respects
.BR BYN_DIR .
No root.
.TP
.B daemon uninstall
Disable and remove the auto-start service.
See
.BR byn-daemon (1).
.SS Diagnostics
.TP
.B version
Print the binary version string.
.TP
.B help \fR[\fICOMMAND\fR]
Print top\-level help, or detailed help for a specific command.
.SH OPTIONS
.SS Global
These flags work \fBbefore or after\fR the subcommand. Conflicting
duplicates are a hard error.
.TP
.B \-\-vault \fINAME\fR
Target vault. Env\-var fallback:
.BR BYN_VAULT .
Defaults to \fIdefault\fR.
.TP
.B \-\-project \fINAME\fR
Target project. Env\-var fallback:
.BR BYN_PROJECT .
Defaults to \fIdefault\fR.
.TP
.B \-\-env \fINAME\fR
Target env. Env\-var fallback:
.BR BYN_ENV .
Defaults to \fIdefault\fR.
.TP
.B \-\-json
Agent mode. Emits machine\-readable output where applicable AND
disables all interactive prompts; an untrusted
.B .byn
file is a hard error instead of a y/N prompt.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-discovery
Skip the
.B .byn
parent\-directory walk for this call. Env\-var alternative:
.BR BYN_NO_DISCOVERY=1 .
.TP
.BR \-\-help ", " \-h
Print command\-specific help and exit.
.SS Subcommand
.TP
.B \-\-password\-stdin
Used by \fBinit\fR and \fBunlock\fR. Read the password from stdin
instead of prompting at the terminal. Useful for automation; the
caller is responsible for not leaking the password via shell
history.
.TP
.B \-\-create\-only
Used by \fBput\fR. Refuse to overwrite an existing secret with that
name.
.TP
.B \-\-foreground
Used by \fBdaemon start\fR. Run in the foreground instead of
detaching. Useful for development and supervised\-service setups.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B BYN_DIR
Override the daemon data directory. Defaults to
.IR ~/.byn .
The daemon places its socket, pidfile, logs, auth\-state, and the
.B vaults/
subtree here.
.TP
.B NO_COLOR
If set to any non\-empty value, disables ANSI color codes in CLI
output. See
.UR https://no-color.org
no\-color.org
.UE .
.TP
.B FORCE_COLOR
If set to any non\-empty value, forces ANSI color codes even when
stderr is not a terminal.
.TP
.B BYN_VAULT, BYN_PROJECT, BYN_ENV
Default scope when the corresponding
.BR \-\-vault ,
.BR \-\-project ,
or
.B \-\-env
flag is not given. CLI flag beats env var beats discovered
.B .byn
beats daemon default.
.TP
.B BYN_NO_DISCOVERY
If set to \fB1\fR, skips the
.B .byn
parent\-directory walk entirely.
.TP
.B BYN_HINTS
If set to \fB0\fR, \fBfalse\fR, \fBoff\fR, or \fBno\fR, suppresses
the short post\-mutation stderr echoes (e.g. "Stored \fIK\fR in
\fIvault/project/env\fR"). Auto\-suppressed when stderr is not a
TTY.
.TP
.B PAGER
Pager binary for
.BR "byn help" .
Default
.B less \-RFX
when available, falling back to
.BR more .
Set
.B PAGER=cat
or
.B BYN_NO_PAGER=1
to disable.
.TP
.B BYN_NO_PAGER
If set to \fB1\fR, disables paging on
.B byn help
output even if
.B $PAGER
is set.
.SH FILES
Under the data root (default
.IR ~/.byn/ ):
.TP
.I config
Optional TOML configuration (no file extension). Recognised keys:
\fB[ui] port\fR (browser admin portal port, default 2967),
\fB[ui] enabled\fR, and \fB[daemon] idle_timeout\fR (Go duration
string; default 15m, set \fB"0s"\fR to disable vault auto\-relock).
Unknown keys are rejected with an error. A missing file uses the
defaults. Loaded at
.BR "byn start" .
.TP
.I daemon.sock
Unix domain socket, mode 0600. The daemon enforces same\-UID access
via the peer credential socket option.
.TP
.I daemon.pid
Pidfile (single\-instance guard). Stale pidfiles are detected via
signal\-0 probe and replaced.
.TP
.I daemon.log
Combined stdout/stderr of a detached daemon (omitted when started
with \fB\-\-foreground\fR).
.TP
.I auth-state.json
Failed\-unlock backoff state. Persisted across daemon restarts so
restarting the daemon doesn't reset the rate limiter.
.TP
.I trusted_byn.json
TOFU records for
.B .byn
files \- a JSON map of canonical paths to SHA\-256 hashes of file
contents. Mode 0600.
.TP
.I audit/<vault>/YYYY-MM.log
Per\-vault append\-only audit log, rolled monthly. NDJSON; one event
per line; each event carries an
.B hmac_chain
field that depends on the previous event's chain (tamper\-evident).
Allowed to be read while the vault is locked.
.PP
Under
.IR vaults/<name>/ :
.TP
.I vault.db
SQLite database. Schema v2: projects, envs, entries, file_meta,
entry_versions, meta.
.TP
.I vault.db-wal, vault.db-shm
SQLite WAL files.
.TP
.I wrapped.key
Argon2id\-wrapped vault key, mode 0600.
.TP
.I meta.json
Vault sidecar: vault_id (UUID v4), wrapped\-key SHA\-256 fingerprint,
creation timestamp. Validated before the password prompt at unlock
so a corrupted or swapped wrapped.key is detected with a clear
diagnostic.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Generic error: bad usage, runtime failure, missing required input.
.TP
.B 2
Daemon unreachable. The CLI prints a recovery hint with the command
to run.
.TP
.B 3
Daemon returned a typed error: wrong password, secret not found,
vault locked, etc.
.SH EXAMPLES
Create and unlock a fresh vault interactively:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ byn init
$ byn unlock
.fi
.RE
.PP
Store and retrieve a credential:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ echo \-n "AKIA..." | byn put aws-access-key
$ byn get aws-access-key
AKIA...
.fi
.RE
.PP
Pipe a secret into another tool without ever materializing it on
disk:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ aws --profile "$(byn get aws-profile)" s3 ls
.fi
.RE
.PP
Use the vault from a script (no interactive prompts):
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ echo "$MASTER_PW" | byn init --password-stdin
$ echo "$MASTER_PW" | byn unlock --password-stdin
.fi
.RE
.PP
Browse the vault visually:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ byn edit
.fi
.RE
.PP
Switch scope per call:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ byn \-\-project myapp \-\-env staging list
$ echo s3cr3t | byn \-\-project myapp put DB_PASSWORD
$ BYN_PROJECT=myapp byn list   # env\-var fallback
.fi
.RE
.PP
Vault / project / env management:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ byn project create myapp
$ byn \-\-project myapp env create staging
$ byn vault list \-\-json | jq '.[].name'
.fi
.RE
.PP
Import a .env / YAML / JSON file:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ byn import .env.local                 # by extension
$ cat config.json | byn import \-\-format json
$ byn import secrets.yaml \-\-dry\-run   # preview
$ byn import .env \-\-skip\-existing     # add\-only
.fi
.RE
.PP
Export back out:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ byn export                            # dotenv to stdout
$ byn export \-\-format json > snapshot.json
$ byn export \-\-output /tmp/dump.env    # 0600 file
.fi
.RE
.PP
Verify everything is healthy and check the audit chain:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ byn doctor
$ byn audit tail \-\-lines 20
$ byn audit verify
.fi
.RE
.PP
Auto\-pick scope from a project directory via
.BR .byn :
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ cat > .byn <<'EOF'
[scope]
project = "myapp"
env = "dev"

[exec]
env = ["DATABASE_URL", "API_KEY"]   # byn exec injects only these
EOF
$ byn trust ./.byn          # first time only
$ byn list                  # uses myapp/dev automatically
$ byn exec -- ./run.sh      # runs ./run.sh with those two injected
.fi
.RE
.PP
Agent\-safe invocation (hard\-fail on untrusted
.BR .byn ,
JSON output for parsing):
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ byn \-\-json list
$ byn \-\-json status
$ byn \-\-no\-discovery list  # bypass .byn entirely
.fi
.RE
.SH SECURITY MODEL
.IP \(bu 2
The daemon is per\-user. Other UIDs are rejected at the socket via
the OS peer\-credential check.
.IP \(bu 2
Secret values are encrypted at rest with XChaCha20\-Poly1305.
AAD\-binding to the entry's vault_id, kind, and name means swapping
ciphertexts across rows within the same vault fails decryption.
.IP \(bu 2
The vault key is wrapped with Argon2id of the master password.
Failed unlock attempts trigger exponential backoff persisted to
disk.
.IP \(bu 2
\fBdoes not\fR defend against a malicious user with the same UID as
the daemon. Memory protection (mlock for master password / Argon2
workspace via
.IR internal/secmem )
is staged but not yet wired into the unlock path \- see deferred
items in
.IR docs/security.md .
.SH ROADMAP
Vault / project / env hierarchy, vault CRUD, project CRUD, env CRUD,
import / export, audit tail + verify, doctor,
.B .byn
discovery + TOFU trust, and a responsive bubbletea TUI are all
shipped. File\-content entries (Phase 5, FUSE materialization),
entry versioning CLI (\fBhistory\fR / \fBrevert\fR / \fBdiff\fR),
the Phase 2 local Web UI, Phase 3 shims, Phase 4 ACLs, and Phase 6
cloud sync remain. See
.IR PLAN.md
for the phased plan.
